48:{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_26","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"rg -n \\\"IntArray::full|zeros\\\\(|sublist|app\\\\(|Zrepeat|replicate|cons\\\\(|tail\\\\(|head\\\\(\\\" /home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/QCP_examples/leetcode /home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming -g '\"'!**/output/**'\"'\"","aggregated_output":"/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:26:          l == app(rev(l1), l2) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:36:            l == app(rev(l1), l2) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:37:            l2 == cons(v_data, l2_new) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:64:The first annotation locates before entering the loop. The `Inv` at the beginning indicates that it is a loop invariant; that is, what program states should satisfy every time before loop condition. Logical variables `l1` and `l2` are existentially quantified. The former represents the reversed first half of the list, and the latter represents the second half to reverse; therefore `l == app(rev(l1), l2)`. In the memory part, `data_at(&w, w_v)` indicates that the address of `w` stores the value `w_v`; similar for `data_at(&p, p_v)`. As discussed in T1, `sll(w_v, l1)` and similarly `sll(v_v, l2)` indicates that the two pointers store the addresses of list heads. Note that the mathematical relation part comes before the memory part.\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:70:The second annotation locates before the loop body. We are about to access `v -> next`, for which we must explicitly state its permission. This can be proved with the help of the fact `v != 0`. Comparing to the first annotation, we also use `l2_new` to represent the tail of `l2`, thus `l2 == cons(v_data, l2_new)`. Please see the following diagram.\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:124:          l == app(rev(l1), l2) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:132:            l == app(rev(l1), l2) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:133:            l2 == cons(v -> data, l2_new) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T3-assertion-and-invariant.md:150:In the second annotation, we replace `exists w_v, data_at(&w, w_v) * sll(w_v, l1)` with `sll(w, l1)`. In `l2 == cons(v -> data, l2_new)`, we implicitly include two memory access: from the address of `v` and from the address of `v -> data`. So it replaces `exists v_v v_data, l2 == cons(v_data, l2_new) && data_at(&v, v_v) * data_at(&(v_v -> data), v_data)`. `sll(v -> next, l2_new)` also includes an access from the address of `v`; this, and the previously mentioned one, are coalesced into one `data_at(&v, v_v)` after being desugared to the basic language.\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:25:          l == app(rev(l1), l2) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:35:            l == app(rev(l1), l2) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:36:            l2 == cons(v_data, l2_new) &&\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:69:When we meet an assertion provided manually, we use that as our symbolic state afterwards and require, by record the condition in the Coq output, that the current symbolic states implies the manual one. The invariant turns the symbolic state to `exists p_v w_v v_v l1 l2, v_v != 0 && l == app(rev(l1), l2) && data_at(&p, p_v) * data_at(&w, w_v) * data_at(&v, v_v) * sll(w_v, l1) * sll(v_v, l2)`.\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:73:After we enter the loop, we know that the loop condition is nonzero. So before the loop body, the symbolic state turns to `exists p_v w_v v_v l1 l2, v_v != 0 && l == app(rev(l1), l2) && data_at(&p, p_v) * data_at(&w, w_v) * data_at(&v, v_v) * sll(w_v, l1) * sll(v_v, l2)`. It is similar to compute the state after the loop, taking the loop condition to be zero. The same also works for `if` and other loop constructs.\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:75:Now we know how to execute until the end of the loop body. Omitting the details, we get `exists p_v w_v v_v v_data v_next l2_new l1 l2, l == app(rev(l1), l2) && l2 == cons(v_data, l2_new) && data_at(&p, p_v) * data_at(&w, v_v) * data_at(&v, v_next) * data_at(&(v_v -> data), v_data) * data_at(&(v_v -> next), w_v) * data_at(&t, v_next) * sll(w_v, l1) * sll(v_next, l2_new)`.\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:79:According to the C semantics, local variables declared inside a pair of curly braces are invisible outside. We must free their memory occupied after the right curly brace. After deleting the variable `t`, the symbolic state after the loop body turns to `exists p_v w_v v_v v_data v_next l2_new l1 l2, l == app(rev(l1), l2) && l2 == cons(v_data, l2_new) && data_at(&p, p_v) * data_at(&w, v_v) * data_at(&v, v_next) * data_at(&(v_v -> data), v_data) * data_at(&(v_v -> next), w_v) * sll(w_v, l1) * sll(v_next, l2_new)`. \n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T4-symbolic-execution.md:85:Finally, we execute `return w;` and ends this function. We compute the value of the return value `w`, here `w_v`, and substitute it for `__return` in the postcondition. The assertion with local variables deleted should imply the substituted postcondition: `forall l p_v w_v v_v l1 l2, v_v == 0 && l == app(rev(l1), l2) && data_at(&p, p_v) * sll(w_v,l1)* sll(v_v,l2) |-- sll(w_v,rev(l))`.\n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T8-function-call.md:53:    Zlength(cons(0, l0)) <= 100 && \n/home/yangfp/QualifiedCProgramming/tutorial/T8-function-call.md:62:Zlength(cons(0, l0)) <= 100 && data_at(&x, 0) * data_at(&q, q_v) * sll(q_v, l0)\n/home/yangfp/Qual